04297nam a22005775i 9780774826617DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20142014xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748266177 a10.59962/97807748266172doi  a(DE-B1597)661077  a(OCoLC)1016746991  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aSOC0620002bisacsh04a305.899/25qOCoLC223/eng/202302161 aMunsterhjelm, Mark, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLiving Dead in the Pacific :bContested Sovereignty and Racism in Genetic Research on Taiwan Aborigines /cMark Munsterhjelm. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (292 p.) :b5 b&w graphs, 3 tables, 2 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures and Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- tAcronyms -- tTaiwan Aborigines’ Genes as Black Boxes -- tAboriginal Peoples’ Genes as Narrated and Contested Assemblages -- tImposing Genetic Distinctions: Aboriginal Peoples and Alcoholism in Genetics Research -- tInformed Consent in the Austronesian Homeland -- tWere the Maori “Made in Taiwan”? -- tInternet Shopping Carts and Patenting Taiwan’s “Gift to the World” -- tConclusion: The Agency of the Living Dead in Contested Sovereignty -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aColonized since the 1600s, Taiwan is largely a nation of settlers. Yet within its population of 23 million are some 500,000 Aboriginal people. Genetic research has permeated both the political and popular spheres as Taiwanese nationalists and Chinese nationalists argue over the significance of migration theories and as the media proliferates genetic theories on predispositions to alcoholism. As this book demonstrates, genetics serve, on the one hand, to reinforce claims to a unique national identity and, on the other hand, to reinforce anti-Aboriginal prejudices. Increasingly, genetic research on Aborigines is being integrated into biotechnology planning, both in the country and through controversial US patent applications. The legacy of this work has been mass violations of the rights of Taiwanese Aborigines. Examining a troubling revival of racially configured genetic research and the questions of sovereignty it raises, Living Dead in the Pacific details a history of exploitation and resistance that represents a new area of conflict facing Aboriginal people both within Taiwan and around the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEthnologyzTaiwan. 0aGeneticsxResearchxPolitical aspectszTaiwan. 0aGeneticsxResearchxSocial aspectszTaiwan. 0aRacismzTaiwan. 0aTaiwan aborigines. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Indigenous Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311127407208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2014z978311127709708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311141999240uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077482661740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774826617423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774826617/original  a978-3-11-127407-2  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  a978-3-11-127709-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2014b2014  a978-3-11-141999-2  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles